[Student "E"]
{[showcards W:SQ N:S2]

The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \SQ, a low card was played from dummy, 

Play the \SK.

It seems that perhaps you should play low and let partner's \SQ force out North's \SA. Then, when you get the lead with a high \C you can force out North's \SJ. Get the lead with your other high \C and set the contract with \Ss.

Suppose you try that. Play low on the first \S. North will also play low and East will be left holding the trick, and also holding the bag! With no more \Ss East will have to play one of the other three suits, and that is just what North wants to have happen. The contract could no longer be beaten.

Now do it the right way. Play your \SK on partner's \SQ. Assume North takes the trick, although it doesn't matter whether he wins the first one or holds up. When you win your first \C drive out North's \SJ. When you win your second \C trick your \Ss will be good. If you overtake the first trick the contract can no longer be made.

Notice that North will always make two \S tricks, so your overtake costs nothing.}
[Play "W"]SQ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "W:A6.K93.Q62.QJ982 K87542.QT4.83.A6 QJT.A7.AK75.T753 93.J8652.JT94.K4"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1C 2S 2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "198dc9bade0a7bc646483d857a5c5f6b92534d32492427e1550b979d13d37be0"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "defense/third_hand_play"]
[Student "E"]
{[showcards W:S9 N:S6]

The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \S9, dummy played the \S6 

Play the \S8 (to signal encouragement).

You could easily win the \SK, then play a small \S to drive out dummy's \SA. But East bid Notrump over your 2\S overcall, so he surely holds \S Q J 10. So when you get the lead with your one \CA entry you can establish your \Ss, but you won't get into the lead to cash them.

Look what happens when you duck the first trick. East will win the trick with his \ST, and start on dummy's \C suit.

South (your wonderful partner) will win the first \C and return his final \S to dummy's \SA.

East will have to keep working on \Cs, but now you can win the \CA and play your \SK, dropping East's \SQ, and your other three good \Ss.

Just like the previous deal, East gets two \S tricks either way, but one way he makes an overtrick, the other way he goes down 2.}
[Play "W"]S9

